<subSubSection id="228F509BFF87FFEB9AC8FE9DFC07FE19" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="6A2A0310FF87FFEB9AC8FE9DFC07FE19" blockId="2.[151,1437,154,502]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">
<emphasis id="58E1DF02FF87FFEB9AC8FE9DFE8EFE65" bold="true" box="[199,331,370,394]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">Etymology:</emphasis>
the species name 
<taxonomicName id="AD957893FF87FFEB9800FE9CFDF5FE65" box="[527,560,371,394]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Cladonota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="58E1DF02FF87FFEB9800FE9CFDF5FE65" box="[527,560,371,394]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is given in honour of the immense contributions of Reginald “Rex” B. Cocroft to humankind’s understanding of treehopper behaviour and ecology. It is utilised as a noun in apposition. 
<emphasis id="58E1DF02FF87FFEB9EE4FE79FAA9FE41" bold="true" box="[1259,1388,406,430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">Discussion:</emphasis>
The setae associated with pronotal pits appear to be sensory in function, as has been previously suggested in other treehopper genera (
<bibRefCitation id="0E047EE1FF87FFEB9AE3FE31FE12FE19" author="Wood, T. K. &amp; Morris, G. K." box="[236,471,478,502]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" pagination="143 - 148" refId="ref2075" refString="Wood, T. K. &amp; Morris, G. K. (1974) Studies on the Function of the Membracid Pronotum (Homoptera): I. Occurence and Distribution of Articulated Hairs. The Canadian Entomologist, 106, 143 - 148. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 106143 - 2" type="journal article" year="1974">Wood &amp; Morris 1974</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0E047EE1FF87FFEB9BEEFE31FD9AFE19" author="Wood, T. K." box="[481,607,478,502]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" pagination="78 - 82" refId="ref2135" refString="Wood, T. K. (1975) Studies on the Function of the Membracid Pronotum (Homoptera): II. Histology. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 77, 78 - 82." type="journal article" year="1975">Wood 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0E047EE1FF87FFEB9865FE31FCC5FE19" author="Dietrich, C. H." box="[618,768,478,502]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" pagination="143 - 152" refId="ref1656" refString="Dietrich, C. H. (1989) Surface sculpturing of the abdominal integument of Membracidae and other Auchenorrhyncha (Homoptera). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 91, 143 - 152." type="journal article" year="1989">Dietrich 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0E047EE1FF87FFEB9903FE31FC73FE19" author="Stegmann, U. E." box="[780,950,478,502]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" pagination="157 - 178" refId="ref1939" refString="Stegmann, U. E. (1998) An exaggerated trait in insects: The prothoracic skeleton of Stictocephala bisonia (Homoptera: Membracidae). Journal of Morphology, 238, 157 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / (SICI) 1097 - 4687 (199811) 238: 2 % 3 C 157 :: AID-JMOR 3 % 3 E 3.0. CO; 2 - H" type="journal article" year="1998">Stegmann 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
